etymologies: late 17th century: from late Latin insufflat- ‘blown into’, from the verb insufflare, from in- ‘into’ + sufflare ‘blow’ (from sub- ‘from below’ + flare ‘to blow’). insufflate (sense 2) dates from the early 20th century

definitions: blow (air, gas, or powder) into a cavity of the body.
shortDefinitions: blow or breathe air, vapour, or powdered medicine into or through body cavity

definitions: blow something into or through (a part of the body).
shortDefinitions: blow or breathe something into or through

definitions: blow or breathe on (someone) to symbolize spiritual influence.
shortDefinitions: breathe on someone to symbolize spiritual influence
